      "role": "user",
      "content": "i hear what ur saying about the \"us vs them\" thing, but isnt that true for almost any group identity? like, even religious groups or local communities have those dynamics. why does nationalism get singled out as being uniquely \"prone\" to being bad or violent? it feels like ur framing nationalism as a problem to be solved rather than just a neutral way for people to organize. isn't it possible that a healthy sense of nationalism is actually the most stable way to govern a state?",
