      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are correct that group dynamics exist everywhere, but nationalism is uniquely dangerous because it often elevates the nation above all other identities, including human rights and international law, to an absolute priority. Unlike local communities or religious groups, which can be inclusive, modern nationalism frequently relies on exclusionary definitions of who belongs, creating a permanent \"other\" that justifies aggression and discrimination. A healthy sense of nationalism can indeed provide stability, but it is only stable when it is subordinated to universal values; when it becomes the supreme moral authority, it inevitably leads to the violent suppression of dissent and minorities.",
